[As mentioned previously, detection of the virus in these bats in Sierra Leone, west Africa, serves as a warning not only in that country and in Uganda, but in other countries where this bat is found. Health care providers need to be aware of this when attending patients with hemorrhagic fevers.

Uganda has reported the majority of Marburg virus infections in bats and in humans. There have been sporadic cases of Marburg virus disease in Uganda in the past.

The virus undoubtedly remains endemic in bats in Sierra Leone as well as in Uganda, and one hopes that public education will result in less human contact with bats there.

ProMED-mail thanks Dr. Aiah Lebbie, Mr. James Bangura, Drs. Brian Bird and Tracey Goldstein as well as Dr. Jonathan Towner for sending in this 1st-hand report. - Mod.TY

